1
00:00:27,298 --> 00:00:29,425
Masumi.

2
00:00:30,093 --> 00:00:31,386
Stop that.

3
00:00:31,970 --> 00:00:34,055
Don't touch dead things.

4
00:00:50,488 --> 00:00:51,322
Hello.

5
00:00:51,823 --> 00:00:53,992
This is Medical Examiner Japan.

6
00:00:58,371 --> 00:01:00,456
Thank you for coming. It's this way.

7
00:01:01,082 --> 00:01:03,084
Yasuo Izawa, 52-year-old male.

8
00:01:03,168 --> 00:01:04,419
Found lying face up

9
00:01:04,502 --> 00:01:07,463
on this road around 1:00 a.m. today
after being hit by a truck.

10
00:01:07,547 --> 00:01:09,632
A passerby called emergency services.

11
00:01:09,716 --> 00:01:14,137
When they arrived, they concluded
he had already passed away.

12
00:01:14,220 --> 00:01:17,807
That man over there is the first witness,
Nobuhiko Yamanuki.

13
00:01:17,891 --> 00:01:20,810
His company handles transportation
for Mr. Izawa's factory.

14
00:01:20,894 --> 00:01:23,104
At our company,
we're all part of a family…

15
00:01:23,188 --> 00:01:26,024
It seems they were somewhat
acquainted through work.

16
00:01:27,650 --> 00:01:28,693
What?

17
00:01:28,776 --> 00:01:29,903
Doctor?

18
00:01:32,697 --> 00:01:35,116
Is this car paint?

19
00:01:35,199 --> 00:01:36,326
Paint fragments?

20
00:01:37,535 --> 00:01:40,413
The same paint is on him here.

21
00:01:40,496 --> 00:01:42,957
There are broken glass fragments
over here too.

22
00:01:44,083 --> 00:01:46,294
Does this mean he was hit by a car?

23
00:01:46,377 --> 00:01:48,296
-Probably.
-No.

24
00:01:48,379 --> 00:01:50,840
We can't be sure of that yet
with just this.

25
00:01:50,924 --> 00:01:53,343
This is near Mr. Izawa's home.

26
00:01:53,426 --> 00:01:56,512
<i>It's believed he was in an accident</i>
<i>while on his way back.</i>

27
00:01:58,014 --> 00:01:59,599
<i>Were there no witnesses?</i>

28
00:01:59,682 --> 00:02:01,226
None so far.

29
00:02:01,309 --> 00:02:04,270
However,
Mr. Izawa's smartphone is missing.

30
00:02:04,354 --> 00:02:06,981
The perpetrator likely took it.

31
00:02:07,941 --> 00:02:10,026
To prevent him from calling for help?

32
00:02:10,109 --> 00:02:11,194
Presumably.

33
00:02:11,277 --> 00:02:12,612
Presumably.

34
00:02:12,695 --> 00:02:14,906
With the scene in mind,

35
00:02:14,989 --> 00:02:17,367
this doesn't look like
a simple traffic accident.

36
00:02:18,701 --> 00:02:19,827
Doctor?

37
00:02:19,911 --> 00:02:21,204
What is it?

38
00:02:22,580 --> 00:02:25,750
The estimated point of impact
based on the paint fragments,

39
00:02:25,833 --> 00:02:28,670
and Mr. Izawa's position
are too close together.

40
00:02:28,753 --> 00:02:30,088
What do you mean?

41
00:02:30,171 --> 00:02:32,340
In a collision with a vehicle,

42
00:02:32,423 --> 00:02:35,134
a person would normally
be thrown further away.

43
00:02:35,218 --> 00:02:37,011
No matter how small the car is,

44
00:02:37,095 --> 00:02:40,223
you are hitting a mass of steel
weighing over 300 kilograms.

45
00:02:41,140 --> 00:02:42,016
It doesn't add up.

46
00:02:42,100 --> 00:02:43,893
You can't say for certain

47
00:02:43,977 --> 00:02:46,521
that these fragments fell
at the moment of impact.

48
00:02:46,604 --> 00:02:50,858
But you could also say that they did.

49
00:02:50,942 --> 00:02:52,902
In other words, it's a mystery.

50
00:02:54,153 --> 00:02:55,530
There's one more issue.

51
00:02:55,613 --> 00:02:56,906
Huh? What is it?

52
00:02:56,990 --> 00:02:58,533
Acceleration marks.

53
00:03:01,160 --> 00:03:04,288
These are marks left
when a car accelerates.

54
00:03:04,372 --> 00:03:06,249
The presence of acceleration marks

55
00:03:06,332 --> 00:03:09,794
implies the car hit Mr. Izawa
at a high speed.

56
00:03:09,877 --> 00:03:13,381
In that case,
he should have landed further away.

57
00:03:13,464 --> 00:03:16,175
So what's your point?

58
00:03:17,510 --> 00:03:20,054
For now, it's a mystery.

59
00:03:20,805 --> 00:03:22,390
-So--
-All right, all right.

60
00:03:22,473 --> 00:03:24,350
I get it, I get it.

61
00:03:40,575 --> 00:03:41,784
Let's begin.

62
00:03:51,794 --> 00:03:55,923
There are signs of bruising
on the back of the head and shoulders.

63
00:03:56,007 --> 00:03:59,969
But I don't believe
this was the fatal blow.

64
00:04:00,053 --> 00:04:04,891
There are also marks on the thigh
resembling a bumper impact,

65
00:04:04,974 --> 00:04:08,144
but that is also unlikely
to be the cause of death.

66
00:04:08,227 --> 00:04:10,229
Upon opening the retroperitoneum,

67
00:04:10,313 --> 00:04:13,191
the tissue around the pelvis
was found to be completely blackened.

68
00:04:13,274 --> 00:04:18,404
<i>The pelvis was severely fractured,</i>
<i>causing massive internal bleeding.</i>

69
00:04:18,488 --> 00:04:21,991
So the cause of death
was internal bleeding?

70
00:04:22,075 --> 00:04:22,909
Yes.

71
00:04:22,992 --> 00:04:26,162
I believe Mr. Izawa's cause of death
was hemorrhagic shock

72
00:04:26,245 --> 00:04:28,122
due to a pelvic fracture.

73
00:04:28,206 --> 00:04:31,542
Well, at least it seems certain
it was a traffic accident.

74
00:04:31,626 --> 00:04:35,171
In a traffic accident,
a person reflexively tries

75
00:04:35,254 --> 00:04:38,007
to protect their body with their arms
at the moment of impact.

76
00:04:38,091 --> 00:04:42,637
Naturally, defense wounds
would remain on one of the arms.

77
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:44,722
However, in Mr. Izawa's case,

78
00:04:44,806 --> 00:04:46,766
there are none.

79
00:04:46,849 --> 00:04:48,059
It doesn't add up.

80
00:04:48,142 --> 00:04:50,353
That is certainly unnatural.

81
00:04:50,436 --> 00:04:52,855
There are not enough injuries
for a collision.

82
00:04:52,939 --> 00:04:55,316
Usually, there are skin tears.

83
00:04:55,400 --> 00:04:56,734
And yet,

84
00:04:56,818 --> 00:04:59,362
there's only one cut
on the back of his hand.

85
00:04:59,445 --> 00:05:00,696
You're right.

86
00:05:03,157 --> 00:05:06,202
The pieces of the puzzle
may be coming together.

87
00:05:07,245 --> 00:05:11,374
If Mr. Izawa's death
was caused by a car collision,

88
00:05:11,457 --> 00:05:13,918
and the pelvic fracture…

89
00:05:14,752 --> 00:05:18,256
Then he must have been hit
by a car moving extremely slowly.

90
00:05:18,339 --> 00:05:20,466
For now, it's a mystery.

91
00:05:20,550 --> 00:05:21,592
-What?
-What?

92
00:05:21,676 --> 00:05:24,220
-What do you mean?
-What do you mean?

93
00:05:24,303 --> 00:05:25,388
Come back…

94
00:05:25,471 --> 00:05:26,848
Yes, excuse me.

95
00:05:27,432 --> 00:05:29,142
Your turn, Dr. Takamori.

96
00:05:29,725 --> 00:05:30,560
Okay.

97
00:05:32,687 --> 00:05:33,646
First,

98
00:05:33,729 --> 00:05:36,524
when hit by a fast car,

99
00:05:36,607 --> 00:05:40,820
you are thrown a significant distance
and suffer various external injuries.

100
00:05:41,737 --> 00:05:45,116
But if hit by a very slow car,

101
00:05:45,199 --> 00:05:47,076
you fall straight backward.

102
00:05:47,577 --> 00:05:49,370
Like a heavy fall on your rear.

103
00:05:50,037 --> 00:05:52,999
In this case, the force is focused
on the center of the body,

104
00:05:53,082 --> 00:05:54,834
which can cause a pelvic fracture.

105
00:05:54,917 --> 00:05:58,087
I see. That would explain
why there are external injuries,

106
00:05:58,171 --> 00:06:00,548
but a severe internal one.

107
00:06:00,631 --> 00:06:01,716
Hang on a second.

108
00:06:02,466 --> 00:06:04,886
How slow is "slow"?

109
00:06:08,931 --> 00:06:10,391
About 20 kilometers per hour?

110
00:06:10,474 --> 00:06:14,061
You can easily avoid a car
moving that slowly, can't you?

111
00:06:14,145 --> 00:06:17,273
At the very least,
it wouldn't be a direct hit.

112
00:06:17,356 --> 00:06:19,233
Then maybe he was hit intentionally?

113
00:06:19,317 --> 00:06:21,736
Don't you think that's a bit of a stretch?

114
00:06:21,819 --> 00:06:23,029
That's right!

115
00:06:24,488 --> 00:06:27,033
Doctor, what do you think?

116
00:06:27,742 --> 00:06:28,576
Well…

117
00:06:31,245 --> 00:06:33,831
If the vehicle was moving fast,

118
00:06:33,915 --> 00:06:35,958
<i>it contradicts the body's distance.</i>

119
00:06:36,042 --> 00:06:38,294
<i>If the vehicle was moving slowly,</i>

120
00:06:38,377 --> 00:06:41,297
<i>there should not be</i>
<i>any acceleration marks.</i>

121
00:06:41,380 --> 00:06:45,218
Several points don't add up,
whether it moved slowly or fast.

122
00:06:45,301 --> 00:06:48,888
<i>And, the lack of defense wounds</i>
<i>remains unexplained.</i>

123
00:06:48,971 --> 00:06:51,057
Considering all of this…

124
00:06:53,392 --> 00:06:54,727
Considering all of that?

125
00:06:57,438 --> 00:06:59,607
For now, it's a mystery.

126
00:07:17,291 --> 00:07:18,125
Yes?

127
00:07:20,711 --> 00:07:21,546
What?

128
00:07:25,007 --> 00:07:26,384
I understand.

129
00:07:28,511 --> 00:07:29,595
Was that Dojima?

130
00:07:30,304 --> 00:07:31,138
Yes.

131
00:07:31,222 --> 00:07:33,057
It seems they found the truck driver.

132
00:07:33,140 --> 00:07:35,142
I would like to hear what he has to say.

133
00:07:35,226 --> 00:07:36,352
Wait, Doctor…

134
00:07:37,270 --> 00:07:39,272
Well, about that…

135
00:07:47,989 --> 00:07:50,533
The deceased is Kazutoshi Tamura,
24 years old.

136
00:07:50,616 --> 00:07:53,160
He was the driver
of the truck in the incident.

137
00:07:53,244 --> 00:07:56,414
A missing person's report
was filed by his transport company.

138
00:07:56,497 --> 00:07:59,959
We confirmed he was using the truck
on the day of the incident.

139
00:08:03,129 --> 00:08:04,964
Anything catch your eye?

140
00:08:06,632 --> 00:08:07,633
Where's the truck?

141
00:08:07,717 --> 00:08:10,011
It was abandoned nearby.

142
00:08:14,890 --> 00:08:17,518
The bumper is dented,
and the paint is chipped.

143
00:08:19,729 --> 00:08:23,232
Mr. Izawa's smartphone
was found in the deceased's pocket.

144
00:08:23,316 --> 00:08:24,358
What?

145
00:08:24,442 --> 00:08:26,068
And on top of that.

146
00:08:28,446 --> 00:08:31,073
This was found in his pocket as well.

147
00:08:31,157 --> 00:08:32,325
The police think

148
00:08:32,408 --> 00:08:35,494
it was a suicide motivated
by remorse over the hit-and-run.

149
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:44,337
The driver suspected of the hit-and-run

150
00:08:45,004 --> 00:08:47,548
was found dead by hanging.

151
00:08:52,970 --> 00:08:55,014
So he killed my husband

152
00:08:56,515 --> 00:08:59,185
and then just took
the easy way out for himself?

153
00:09:02,146 --> 00:09:04,023
How could this happen?

154
00:09:07,068 --> 00:09:10,029
I understand how you feel.

155
00:09:13,616 --> 00:09:18,746
Do you recognize this man named Tamura?

156
00:09:19,914 --> 00:09:22,333
Anything at all will help.

157
00:09:24,543 --> 00:09:28,839
He has come to our factory a few times.

158
00:09:30,549 --> 00:09:33,552
I think he was in charge
of our deliveries.

159
00:09:35,179 --> 00:09:39,600
Did you notice anything
strange about their relationship?

160
00:09:41,519 --> 00:09:42,603
One time,

161
00:09:42,687 --> 00:09:46,982
<i>I saw the two of them having an argument.</i>

162
00:09:47,608 --> 00:09:50,861
Do you know what it was about?

163
00:09:52,113 --> 00:09:54,740
I couldn't hear any details.

164
00:09:54,824 --> 00:09:59,578
When I asked my husband
if he was all right,

165
00:10:00,204 --> 00:10:02,331
I got no clear answer.

166
00:10:03,290 --> 00:10:07,336
Would you say they were
on bad terms with each other?

167
00:10:08,921 --> 00:10:09,964
No.

168
00:10:10,047 --> 00:10:11,465
I don't think they were.

169
00:10:13,384 --> 00:10:17,179
Did they often meet with each other?

170
00:10:20,516 --> 00:10:22,977
I don't know any details, but…

171
00:10:23,686 --> 00:10:27,398
I think they met a few times every month.

172
00:10:29,942 --> 00:10:32,069
Thank you.

173
00:10:37,533 --> 00:10:39,410
<i>He hits him with his truck,</i>

174
00:10:39,493 --> 00:10:42,037
and then commits suicide over the guilt.

175
00:10:42,621 --> 00:10:44,123
That's the size of it, right?

176
00:10:44,206 --> 00:10:46,792
We don't currently know.

177
00:10:47,501 --> 00:10:51,338
If they had some bad blood
between each other for whatever reason,

178
00:10:51,422 --> 00:10:54,800
then it's a possibility he hit him
with his truck on purpose, isn't it?

179
00:10:55,634 --> 00:10:59,472
We don't currently know that either.

180
00:11:00,556 --> 00:11:02,183
You're right.

181
00:11:02,933 --> 00:11:04,018
Sorry.

182
00:11:04,643 --> 00:11:07,313
However,
there is one thing that caught my eye.

183
00:11:08,272 --> 00:11:09,106
What is it?

184
00:11:09,190 --> 00:11:12,485
The condition of Tamura's body
at the scene.

185
00:11:12,568 --> 00:11:15,404
Normally, when one dies
from asphyxiation from hanging,

186
00:11:15,488 --> 00:11:17,490
their face becomes pale.

187
00:11:17,573 --> 00:11:21,619
<i>However, Tamura's complexion</i>
<i>looked just fine.</i>

188
00:11:21,702 --> 00:11:24,246
He had all the color in his face, right?

189
00:11:24,330 --> 00:11:25,414
Yes.

190
00:11:25,998 --> 00:11:26,916
Therefore…

191
00:11:33,839 --> 00:11:34,882
Let's begin.

192
00:11:43,807 --> 00:11:44,975
It's over here!

193
00:11:46,477 --> 00:11:49,230
YAMANUKI SHIPPING CO., LTD.

194
00:11:49,313 --> 00:11:54,109
Could you tell us about
how Kazutoshi Tamura was at work?

195
00:11:54,693 --> 00:11:55,819
Right…

196
00:11:55,903 --> 00:11:57,238
Tamura…

197
00:11:59,240 --> 00:12:03,160
It honestly pains me
to speak ill of the dead.

198
00:12:03,244 --> 00:12:05,079
Were there any problems?

199
00:12:06,288 --> 00:12:09,333
<i>He was often found sleeping</i>
<i>in the middle of work.</i>

200
00:12:09,416 --> 00:12:10,751
Are you okay?

201
00:12:11,377 --> 00:12:12,294
Sorry.

202
00:12:12,920 --> 00:12:14,547
He was not very bright.

203
00:12:17,216 --> 00:12:18,342
What are you doing?

204
00:12:18,425 --> 00:12:21,595
<i>To be honest,</i>
<i>I wasn't sure what to do about him.</i>

205
00:12:23,889 --> 00:12:25,683
I didn't really want to do this,

206
00:12:25,766 --> 00:12:28,310
but I attached a GPS to his truck
to monitor him.

207
00:12:28,394 --> 00:12:30,187
A GPS…

208
00:12:30,271 --> 00:12:33,357
We also have the shift records over there.

209
00:12:33,440 --> 00:12:36,235
-Please look at them if needed.
-Thank you very much.

210
00:12:45,619 --> 00:12:46,453
Hey.

211
00:12:46,537 --> 00:12:47,580
Yes, sorry!

212
00:12:52,376 --> 00:12:55,921
There was mild pulmonary edema
in his lungs.

213
00:12:56,839 --> 00:12:59,633
This can be a sign of asphyxiation,

214
00:12:59,717 --> 00:13:03,220
but also a sign of heart failure
or death from poisoning.

215
00:13:03,304 --> 00:13:04,930
The CT scan results show

216
00:13:05,014 --> 00:13:07,349
that the decisive blow
wasn't to the heart or brain.

217
00:13:07,433 --> 00:13:09,018
It doesn't seem like heart failure.

218
00:13:09,101 --> 00:13:10,436
Thank you.

219
00:13:11,103 --> 00:13:12,938
Next, on the neck,

220
00:13:13,022 --> 00:13:16,400
there are clear rope marks left.

221
00:13:16,483 --> 00:13:18,569
So, he died by hanging?

222
00:13:18,652 --> 00:13:21,530
We can't draw a conclusion just from that.

223
00:13:21,614 --> 00:13:23,699
Because you can make it look like

224
00:13:23,782 --> 00:13:26,410
someone hanged themselves
after killing them, right?

225
00:13:26,493 --> 00:13:27,620
Yes.

226
00:13:27,703 --> 00:13:31,915
There is one more thing
that caught my eye during the autopsy.

227
00:13:32,583 --> 00:13:34,043
<i>Thank you for your cooperation.</i>

228
00:13:34,126 --> 00:13:36,003
No, I'm happy to help with this.

229
00:13:36,086 --> 00:13:37,504
Well then, goodbye.

230
00:13:38,213 --> 00:13:39,757
By the way…

231
00:13:41,592 --> 00:13:45,179
you wouldn't know about any trouble
Izawa was having, would you?

232
00:13:45,262 --> 00:13:46,680
Trouble?

233
00:13:47,473 --> 00:13:49,224
Trouble…

234
00:13:49,308 --> 00:13:50,184
Well…

235
00:13:50,267 --> 00:13:51,477
Did you think of something?

236
00:13:51,560 --> 00:13:53,395
Well, it's only a rumor.

237
00:13:53,479 --> 00:13:55,230
Only a rumor?

238
00:13:55,314 --> 00:13:56,732
Actually…

239
00:13:59,568 --> 00:14:00,819
Take a look at this.

240
00:14:01,612 --> 00:14:04,281
There are few petechial hemorrhages
behind the eyes.

241
00:14:04,365 --> 00:14:05,991
<i>In cases of asphyxiation,</i>

242
00:14:06,075 --> 00:14:09,119
<i>blood that should flow down</i>
<i>from the neck pools,</i>

243
00:14:09,203 --> 00:14:12,206
<i>and there should be</i>
<i>signs of bleeding behind the eyes.</i>

244
00:14:12,289 --> 00:14:14,875
If it wasn't hanging, then what was it?

245
00:14:15,501 --> 00:14:18,253
We're still missing some pieces.

246
00:14:20,005 --> 00:14:22,091
How was the autopsy for Kazutoshi Tamura?

247
00:14:22,174 --> 00:14:23,425
How was it?

248
00:14:23,509 --> 00:14:26,637
We couldn't conclude
that Tamura's cause of death was hanging.

249
00:14:26,720 --> 00:14:27,888
I see.

250
00:14:27,972 --> 00:14:29,181
What about you?

251
00:14:30,182 --> 00:14:31,767
We learned something interesting.

252
00:14:33,102 --> 00:14:37,648
Izawa had been in debt
for two years to run the factory.

253
00:14:37,731 --> 00:14:39,441
Nearly 100 million yen.

254
00:14:39,525 --> 00:14:40,943
What? 100 million?

255
00:14:41,026 --> 00:14:42,027
That's not all.

256
00:14:42,111 --> 00:14:45,447
A 100 million yen life insurance policy
was taken out on Izawa.

257
00:14:45,531 --> 00:14:48,701
And it's only been three months
since he signed it.

258
00:14:48,784 --> 00:14:51,412
I see it as money to protect the company.

259
00:14:51,495 --> 00:14:55,290
The police are moving forward with
the investigation as a case

260
00:14:55,374 --> 00:14:57,292
<i>of induced suicide by Akemi Izawa.</i>

261
00:14:57,793 --> 00:15:00,546
Wait, what does that mean?

262
00:15:01,505 --> 00:15:05,092
We mean that she induced Izawa
to commit suicide

263
00:15:05,175 --> 00:15:07,469
and make it look like an accident.

264
00:15:07,553 --> 00:15:10,347
To get the 100 million
from the life insurance policy.

265
00:15:10,431 --> 00:15:11,807
No, wait.

266
00:15:12,516 --> 00:15:13,559
If that's true,

267
00:15:13,642 --> 00:15:17,646
then why would the driver,
Tamura, have to die?

268
00:15:18,355 --> 00:15:22,776
If it's discovered he committed suicide,
then she won't get the 100 million.

269
00:15:22,860 --> 00:15:25,154
<i>She killed the driver, Kazutoshi Tamura,</i>

270
00:15:25,237 --> 00:15:28,157
<i>and made it look like a suicide.</i>

271
00:15:29,324 --> 00:15:32,453
Then it would make sense
that he didn't have much hemorrhaging

272
00:15:32,536 --> 00:15:35,247
because he didn't die of asphyxiation.

273
00:15:35,330 --> 00:15:39,710
That may also explain why Izawa
didn't dodge a slow-moving truck.

274
00:15:39,793 --> 00:15:42,087
<i>Because she hesitated</i>
<i>to run over her husband,</i>

275
00:15:42,171 --> 00:15:44,423
<i>Akemi hit Mr. Izawa</i>
<i>at a half-hearted speed.</i>

276
00:15:45,257 --> 00:15:47,593
Does that mean Akemi is the culprit?

277
00:15:47,676 --> 00:15:49,887
We'll go ask the suspect directly.

278
00:15:49,970 --> 00:15:52,556
Yes. We'll check with the insurance
company for--

279
00:15:52,639 --> 00:15:53,599
Don't dawdle!

280
00:15:53,682 --> 00:15:54,808
Yes, ma'am!

281
00:15:54,892 --> 00:15:56,268
I'll get the referral!

282
00:16:07,446 --> 00:16:08,489
Doctor,

283
00:16:09,198 --> 00:16:10,532
what do you think?

284
00:16:27,633 --> 00:16:29,843
<i>The night of the accident?</i>

285
00:16:29,927 --> 00:16:31,678
I was at home.

286
00:16:32,930 --> 00:16:35,390
I see.

287
00:16:36,058 --> 00:16:39,269
I'm under suspicion, aren't I?

288
00:16:40,229 --> 00:16:43,023
Oh, no, it's nothing like that.

289
00:16:44,358 --> 00:16:46,360
A police officer came by earlier, too,

290
00:16:47,236 --> 00:16:50,114
and asked me all sorts of things.

291
00:16:55,244 --> 00:16:58,622
Like about how managing the factory
wasn't going well,

292
00:16:59,581 --> 00:17:01,917
and about my husband's
life insurance money.

293
00:17:03,168 --> 00:17:08,799
I wonder if they think I killed him
for the insurance money.

294
00:17:09,466 --> 00:17:11,593
No, we're not saying that.

295
00:17:11,677 --> 00:17:14,138
Just because we have debts to pay back…

296
00:17:14,221 --> 00:17:17,766
I haven't fallen so low
as to commit murder.

297
00:17:20,227 --> 00:17:21,645
I'm very sorry.

298
00:17:23,605 --> 00:17:25,607
You have a child, huh?

299
00:17:30,154 --> 00:17:31,363
Yes.

300
00:17:32,197 --> 00:17:33,031
Well…

301
00:17:35,576 --> 00:17:36,827
Kazuki…

302
00:17:38,871 --> 00:17:41,832
passed away ten years ago.

303
00:17:45,085 --> 00:17:46,378
It was suicide.

304
00:17:49,089 --> 00:17:50,257
Kazuki

305
00:17:51,091 --> 00:17:52,217
was a serious boy.

306
00:17:53,427 --> 00:17:55,179
But he was clumsy,

307
00:17:55,262 --> 00:17:57,264
and everything he tried

308
00:17:57,347 --> 00:17:59,683
seemed to go nowhere.

309
00:18:01,435 --> 00:18:04,438
<i>His job hunting didn't go well either.</i>

310
00:18:10,861 --> 00:18:12,196
REJECTION NOTICE

311
00:18:12,279 --> 00:18:13,197
<i>Kazuki.</i>

312
00:18:13,864 --> 00:18:14,907
I'm coming in.

313
00:18:25,042 --> 00:18:26,919
Is it not going well?

314
00:18:29,504 --> 00:18:30,672
Dad, actually…

315
00:18:30,756 --> 00:18:31,632
What?

316
00:18:32,633 --> 00:18:36,428
Would it be okay
if I worked for your company?

317
00:18:39,097 --> 00:18:41,975
Even if you join us, you'll only suffer.

318
00:18:43,393 --> 00:18:45,896
Why don't you keep at it
just a little bit longer?

319
00:18:50,275 --> 00:18:53,779
<i>My husband didn't really want</i>
<i>him to join the company,</i>

320
00:18:55,948 --> 00:18:58,867
but to find a better job,

321
00:18:59,701 --> 00:19:02,079
and become happy.

322
00:19:07,334 --> 00:19:08,502
But that day…

323
00:19:09,127 --> 00:19:10,921
Kazuki, I'm coming in.

324
00:19:11,546 --> 00:19:12,673
I've got breakfast--

325
00:19:15,175 --> 00:19:17,886
<i>It was my husband who found Kazuki</i>

326
00:19:19,054 --> 00:19:20,389
<i>after he had hanged himself.</i>

327
00:19:27,020 --> 00:19:29,064
My husband thought that if only

328
00:19:30,107 --> 00:19:33,068
he had noticed Kazuki's
suffering back then, Kazuki would…

329
00:19:34,444 --> 00:19:37,447
My husband always blamed himself for it.

330
00:19:40,033 --> 00:19:41,118
Day…

331
00:19:43,620 --> 00:19:44,663
after day…

332
00:19:51,378 --> 00:19:54,548
I would never do such a thing.

333
00:20:02,222 --> 00:20:04,182
I don't think it's possible after all.

334
00:20:07,144 --> 00:20:10,022
I don't think someone
who cares so much for their family

335
00:20:10,856 --> 00:20:13,275
would commit instigation of suicide.

336
00:20:16,069 --> 00:20:21,450
You cannot conclude
whether a parent is truly

337
00:20:23,076 --> 00:20:24,661
thinking of their child.

338
00:20:49,936 --> 00:20:53,231
The doctor was kind of strange today.

339
00:20:53,940 --> 00:20:56,276
From what I know, he just seems like that.

340
00:20:57,402 --> 00:20:58,612
Well, yes.

341
00:20:59,321 --> 00:21:01,198
He's always calm and collected, right?

342
00:21:01,281 --> 00:21:02,949
He just does sudoku.

343
00:21:03,617 --> 00:21:04,493
Yeah.

344
00:21:05,202 --> 00:21:06,036
Oh.

345
00:21:06,536 --> 00:21:09,331
Maybe it's just not a topic
he's comfortable with.

346
00:21:10,332 --> 00:21:11,416
Not comfortable?

347
00:21:12,042 --> 00:21:14,795
Like parental love?
It's not that uncommon.

348
00:21:56,461 --> 00:21:59,631
I'm very sorry about the other day…

349
00:22:04,010 --> 00:22:08,098
I visited the factory,
but you weren't there.

350
00:22:08,932 --> 00:22:12,018
I've decided to close down the factory.

351
00:22:14,271 --> 00:22:17,274
The management
wasn't going well to begin with.

352
00:22:18,859 --> 00:22:20,777
And my husband is gone now, too.

353
00:22:34,416 --> 00:22:35,500
Ma'am,

354
00:22:36,585 --> 00:22:38,920
if it's all right with you,

355
00:22:39,004 --> 00:22:41,464
could we investigate inside the house?

356
00:22:43,133 --> 00:22:45,552
We might find some kind of clue.

357
00:22:51,600 --> 00:22:55,812
I want to find out exactly
what happened on the day of the incident.

358
00:22:57,272 --> 00:22:58,732
For your husband's sake.

359
00:23:01,943 --> 00:23:03,945
Above all, for your own sake.

360
00:23:11,077 --> 00:23:13,580
<i>He's coming up from the rear!</i>

361
00:23:13,663 --> 00:23:15,332
Go, go, go!

362
00:23:16,499 --> 00:23:18,126
-All right!
-Wow.

363
00:23:18,210 --> 00:23:19,544
You did it.

364
00:23:19,628 --> 00:23:20,587
What?

365
00:23:20,670 --> 00:23:21,755
Right.

366
00:23:23,757 --> 00:23:25,508
Is there anyone here

367
00:23:25,592 --> 00:23:29,930
who used the same truck
as the late Mr. Tamura?

368
00:23:30,889 --> 00:23:32,432
I have.

369
00:23:32,515 --> 00:23:33,934
-Great!
-Me too.

370
00:23:34,017 --> 00:23:34,893
Great!

371
00:23:35,602 --> 00:23:38,521
Have you felt unwell
in the past few weeks?

372
00:23:39,397 --> 00:23:41,107
Just a little dizzy.

373
00:23:41,191 --> 00:23:42,901
I had a cold.

374
00:23:44,486 --> 00:23:45,946
Thank you very much.

375
00:23:46,029 --> 00:23:48,782
There is something I would like to check.

376
00:23:50,033 --> 00:23:53,036
This is the truck
he was driving that night.

377
00:23:53,119 --> 00:23:54,454
Oh, I see.

378
00:23:58,500 --> 00:24:00,418
Oh, may I borrow this?

379
00:24:04,547 --> 00:24:07,008
Hey… Are you okay?

380
00:24:07,092 --> 00:24:09,219
Oh, don't worry.

381
00:24:17,310 --> 00:24:19,479
I'm sorry to be so forward.

382
00:24:19,562 --> 00:24:21,189
No…

383
00:24:27,696 --> 00:24:29,990
If I take anything that seems of interest,

384
00:24:30,073 --> 00:24:32,033
even if I don't understand what it is,

385
00:24:32,659 --> 00:24:35,495
Dr. Masumi might notice something.

386
00:24:38,999 --> 00:24:40,625
Well, in that case,

387
00:24:41,376 --> 00:24:44,587
would you like to check Kazuki's room too?

388
00:24:45,213 --> 00:24:46,298
What?

389
00:24:50,927 --> 00:24:52,095
This is it.

390
00:24:55,098 --> 00:24:59,602
We've left it just as it was
since Kazuki passed.

391
00:25:01,438 --> 00:25:02,897
Neither I nor my husband

392
00:25:03,565 --> 00:25:05,567
could quite accept it.

393
00:25:11,114 --> 00:25:12,532
If you would like,

394
00:25:13,700 --> 00:25:15,618
could you investigate it?

395
00:25:17,162 --> 00:25:17,996
Yes.

396
00:25:20,415 --> 00:25:21,708
Thank you very much.

397
00:25:24,377 --> 00:25:25,253
I'll go in then.

398
00:25:43,146 --> 00:25:45,148
I used to have one of these, too.

399
00:25:46,149 --> 00:25:49,027
When I first started working,
I tried to act like an adult.

400
00:25:51,404 --> 00:25:53,281
That fountain pen

401
00:25:54,032 --> 00:25:56,951
is something my husband
gave to Kazuki as a present.

402
00:25:57,952 --> 00:26:00,538
When his job hunting wasn't going well,

403
00:26:00,622 --> 00:26:03,041
he told him that if he used it
to write his resumes,

404
00:26:03,124 --> 00:26:04,292
he would be fine.

405
00:26:17,472 --> 00:26:18,640
I'm back!

406
00:26:18,723 --> 00:26:20,141
Ms. Kiryu, what's all that?

407
00:26:20,225 --> 00:26:22,310
I got permission from Akemi

408
00:26:22,394 --> 00:26:24,354
and borrowed some of his belongings.

409
00:26:24,437 --> 00:26:25,563
This much?

410
00:26:25,647 --> 00:26:26,523
Yes.

411
00:26:28,149 --> 00:26:29,067
Everyone.

412
00:26:29,150 --> 00:26:31,403
Could you help me investigate everything?

413
00:26:31,486 --> 00:26:33,446
How are we going to handle all this?

414
00:26:33,530 --> 00:26:36,032
I'm busy too, you know. I'll pass.

415
00:26:36,116 --> 00:26:37,158
Please.

416
00:26:37,784 --> 00:26:39,077
I'm asking you.

417
00:26:41,788 --> 00:26:43,540
Dr. Masumi, you too, please.

418
00:26:47,001 --> 00:26:49,796
I just can't believe Akemi is the culprit.

419
00:26:50,422 --> 00:26:54,509
So, I thought you might be able
to find some kind of clue.

420
00:26:56,594 --> 00:26:57,679
Please.

421
00:26:58,513 --> 00:26:59,764
Of course.

422
00:27:00,390 --> 00:27:01,683
Thank you very much.

423
00:27:02,684 --> 00:27:03,726
All right.

424
00:27:05,270 --> 00:27:07,355
You too, Dr. Matsubara.

425
00:27:07,439 --> 00:27:08,940
-Ugh.
-Come on.

426
00:27:09,023 --> 00:27:11,192
I've got a show I want to watch!

427
00:27:11,276 --> 00:27:13,027
Just record it, then.

428
00:27:14,612 --> 00:27:15,864
Here, thank you.

429
00:27:18,783 --> 00:27:19,617
All right.

430
00:27:24,330 --> 00:27:25,206
Hey.

431
00:27:25,999 --> 00:27:30,378
This is a gift Izawa gave to Kazuki
when he was job hunting.

432
00:27:38,303 --> 00:27:40,555
-What were Tamura's blood test results?
-Hold on.

433
00:27:41,055 --> 00:27:42,015
Where are they…

434
00:27:43,808 --> 00:27:44,851
Here.

435
00:27:46,603 --> 00:27:48,062
Acetaminophen.

436
00:27:50,899 --> 00:27:52,650
What is that?

437
00:27:53,651 --> 00:27:56,571
It's an ingredient often found
in things like cold medicine.

438
00:28:07,040 --> 00:28:08,416
<i>You can make it look like</i>

439
00:28:08,500 --> 00:28:10,084
<i>someone hanged themselves…</i>

440
00:28:10,168 --> 00:28:11,461
<i>…no defense wounds.</i>

441
00:28:11,544 --> 00:28:13,254
<i>There's only one cut</i>
<i>on the back of his hand.</i>

442
00:28:13,338 --> 00:28:14,547
Just a little dizzy.

443
00:28:14,631 --> 00:28:15,965
I had a cold.

444
00:28:16,049 --> 00:28:18,801
<i>Kazuki passed away ten years ago.</i>

445
00:28:18,885 --> 00:28:21,846
<i>This is a gift Izawa gave to Kazuki</i>
<i>when he was job hunting.</i>

446
00:28:21,930 --> 00:28:23,556
<i>Acetaminophen.</i>

447
00:28:23,640 --> 00:28:26,351
I think they met a few times every month.

448
00:28:41,825 --> 00:28:43,368
The pieces may be

449
00:28:45,286 --> 00:28:47,330
coming together.

450
00:29:04,097 --> 00:29:06,850
MUSASHINODAI POLICE OFFICE

451
00:29:14,566 --> 00:29:17,777
Thank you for coming while you're so busy.

452
00:29:17,861 --> 00:29:20,947
There is something
I would like to ask you about.

453
00:29:21,447 --> 00:29:23,700
I'm sorry, but I'm busy,

454
00:29:23,783 --> 00:29:26,160
so could we finish this
as quickly as possible?

455
00:29:27,203 --> 00:29:28,204
I understand.

456
00:29:36,379 --> 00:29:37,213
Right this way.

457
00:29:40,550 --> 00:29:41,718
Please, have a seat here.

458
00:29:41,801 --> 00:29:42,635
Okay.

459
00:29:45,805 --> 00:29:51,269
These are photos taken
when I visited your company the other day.

460
00:29:53,730 --> 00:29:55,732
You can't just take liberties like that.

461
00:29:55,815 --> 00:29:57,483
I'm terribly sorry.

462
00:29:58,151 --> 00:30:01,613
I just had something
that was bothering me.

463
00:30:04,699 --> 00:30:07,702
This is the truck Tamura
drove on the night of the incident.

464
00:30:07,785 --> 00:30:09,370
Please look at this part.

465
00:30:09,454 --> 00:30:11,080
The pipe is broken.

466
00:30:11,831 --> 00:30:16,294
Also, there are cracks in the welding
several centimeters big.

467
00:30:18,421 --> 00:30:21,382
And there is one more thing
that concerns me.

468
00:30:24,385 --> 00:30:27,805
Tamura had been suffering from symptoms

469
00:30:27,889 --> 00:30:31,184
like dizziness and a cold
for several weeks.

470
00:30:31,267 --> 00:30:32,644
Strangely,

471
00:30:33,311 --> 00:30:38,441
there were several others
suffering from similar symptoms.

472
00:30:38,524 --> 00:30:40,443
It's just a coincidence.

473
00:30:40,526 --> 00:30:42,737
Everyone at our company works hard,

474
00:30:42,820 --> 00:30:45,323
so it wouldn't be strange
for them to fall ill.

475
00:30:46,741 --> 00:30:50,954
I do not believe
that it was a coincidence.

476
00:30:52,580 --> 00:30:54,123
On what grounds?

477
00:30:54,707 --> 00:30:56,334
I believe the workers

478
00:30:56,417 --> 00:31:01,297
were suffering from
carbon monoxide poisoning.

479
00:31:03,466 --> 00:31:05,510
On the day of the incident,

480
00:31:05,593 --> 00:31:07,595
<i>Tamura parked the truck on the street,</i>

481
00:31:07,679 --> 00:31:11,516
<i>and exhausted from working all day,</i>
<i>took a nap.</i>

482
00:31:13,017 --> 00:31:14,143
That day,

483
00:31:14,227 --> 00:31:16,729
it was very humid,
even when the sun went down.

484
00:31:17,981 --> 00:31:21,693
<i>He most likely left the air conditioner on</i>
<i>while inside the vehicle.</i>

485
00:31:23,027 --> 00:31:26,698
<i>If you continue to run it</i>
<i>while parked for a long time,</i>

486
00:31:27,490 --> 00:31:32,829
<i>exhaust gas will begin to accumulate</i>
<i>under the vehicle from that broken pipe.</i>

487
00:31:33,871 --> 00:31:35,373
<i>As a result,</i>

488
00:31:35,456 --> 00:31:37,709
<i>carbon monoxide,</i>
<i>which is lighter than air,</i>

489
00:31:37,792 --> 00:31:42,755
<i>leaked through the crack</i>
<i>in the bottom of the vehicle.</i>

490
00:31:44,257 --> 00:31:47,802
Tamura, who was sleep-deprived,
had fallen into a deep sleep.

491
00:31:47,885 --> 00:31:51,472
And without even realizing it himself,

492
00:31:51,973 --> 00:31:54,892
he was suffering
from carbon monoxide poisoning.

493
00:31:55,935 --> 00:32:00,690
The reason his complexion looked normal
when his body was found

494
00:32:00,773 --> 00:32:02,400
was because of that.

495
00:32:04,569 --> 00:32:07,697
But what was more decisive than anything…

496
00:32:09,782 --> 00:32:10,867
was this.

497
00:32:12,869 --> 00:32:14,454
I'M SORRY FOR BEING LIKE THIS

498
00:32:15,413 --> 00:32:19,333
This note,
found at the scene of the incident.

499
00:32:20,752 --> 00:32:22,128
And that alone

500
00:32:23,921 --> 00:32:25,423
doesn't add up.

501
00:32:25,506 --> 00:32:26,632
What?

502
00:32:27,383 --> 00:32:28,634
Why?

503
00:32:31,137 --> 00:32:36,059
Initially, we thought this note
was a suicide note left by the driver,

504
00:32:36,142 --> 00:32:37,769
Kazutoshi Tamura.

505
00:32:39,937 --> 00:32:41,314
But we were wrong.

506
00:32:43,232 --> 00:32:45,151
What do you mean?

507
00:32:47,195 --> 00:32:49,489
It was written by your late son.

508
00:32:51,741 --> 00:32:52,909
What…

509
00:32:53,826 --> 00:32:58,414
These letters haven't bled
through to the back of the paper.

510
00:32:59,332 --> 00:33:03,377
The ink has not been absorbed
into the paper.

511
00:33:04,087 --> 00:33:05,880
If it were oil-based,
it would bleed through.

512
00:33:06,380 --> 00:33:09,967
If it were water-based,
it should smudge because of the paper.

513
00:33:10,510 --> 00:33:12,887
But it is neither of those.

514
00:33:13,513 --> 00:33:17,517
Pigmented gel ink is what it's called.

515
00:33:17,600 --> 00:33:20,144
Pigmented gel ink?

516
00:33:20,228 --> 00:33:26,275
Can you see the fine cracks in the ink
on the surface of these letters?

517
00:33:26,776 --> 00:33:30,279
A characteristic of pigmented gel ink
is that it cracks

518
00:33:30,363 --> 00:33:33,324
after several years of exposure to air.

519
00:33:33,825 --> 00:33:36,202
<i>In other words, that means</i>

520
00:33:36,285 --> 00:33:41,332
this note was written several years ago.

521
00:33:43,251 --> 00:33:44,877
And this ink

522
00:33:44,961 --> 00:33:46,587
matches the fountain pen

523
00:33:46,671 --> 00:33:51,551
that Izawa's son, Kazuki, used to love.

524
00:33:53,469 --> 00:33:56,097
I believe your husband
kept it with him at all times

525
00:33:56,806 --> 00:34:00,601
<i>as a form of atonement.</i>

526
00:34:04,689 --> 00:34:06,691
Why would something Kazuki wrote

527
00:34:07,358 --> 00:34:09,068
be inside the truck?

528
00:34:09,986 --> 00:34:11,279
I believe…

529
00:34:13,156 --> 00:34:15,867
your husband was trying to help Tamura.

530
00:34:20,830 --> 00:34:23,749
<i>That night, when Izawa was going home…</i>

531
00:34:24,584 --> 00:34:25,543
Hey!

532
00:34:25,626 --> 00:34:27,128
Are you sleeping?

533
00:34:28,045 --> 00:34:30,131
You'll catch a cold!

534
00:34:31,424 --> 00:34:32,258
Hey!

535
00:34:32,341 --> 00:34:34,927
Hey, are you okay? Hey!

536
00:34:49,609 --> 00:34:50,985
Hey, what's wrong?

537
00:34:51,068 --> 00:34:53,404
Hey! Pull yourself together!

538
00:34:53,487 --> 00:34:55,531
Hey!

539
00:34:56,532 --> 00:34:57,366
Hey…

540
00:34:57,450 --> 00:34:58,367
All right…

541
00:34:59,869 --> 00:35:04,665
<i>Izawa inhaled carbon monoxide</i>
<i>from the vehicle.</i>

542
00:35:12,340 --> 00:35:15,384
Is that bastard
seriously slacking off again?

543
00:35:27,980 --> 00:35:28,856
Hey!

544
00:35:29,815 --> 00:35:30,983
What happened?

545
00:35:34,612 --> 00:35:35,780
The truck…

546
00:35:37,240 --> 00:35:38,824
Something's wrong with it.

547
00:35:38,908 --> 00:35:40,243
What?

548
00:35:40,326 --> 00:35:41,911
I'm so dizzy.

549
00:35:54,799 --> 00:35:55,633
Hey.

550
00:35:56,550 --> 00:35:57,551
Are you okay?

551
00:35:58,803 --> 00:36:00,930
If this gets out, my company is ruined.

552
00:36:01,722 --> 00:36:03,224
Hey…

553
00:36:04,225 --> 00:36:05,351
Are you okay?

554
00:36:06,185 --> 00:36:07,144
Can you stand?

555
00:36:07,770 --> 00:36:09,563
I finally climbed my way to the top…

556
00:37:05,995 --> 00:37:08,956
<i>And, after that, Yamanuki…</i>

557
00:37:13,127 --> 00:37:15,379
I'M SORRY FOR BEING LIKE THIS

558
00:37:18,549 --> 00:37:21,761
<i>He was desperately trying</i>
<i>to make it look like an accident.</i>

559
00:37:26,724 --> 00:37:28,517
<i>He put Tamura into the truck,</i>

560
00:37:29,018 --> 00:37:30,186
<i>and fled the scene.</i>

561
00:37:42,990 --> 00:37:45,284
<i>Tamura made it look like</i>
<i>he committed suicide.</i>

562
00:37:48,996 --> 00:37:51,707
Considering the above,

563
00:37:53,376 --> 00:37:57,505
I believe the reason Yasuo Izawa
had no defensive wounds

564
00:37:58,631 --> 00:38:05,638
was that he was trying to protect Tamura,
who was unconscious at the time.

565
00:38:10,142 --> 00:38:13,312
If you had called an ambulance right then,

566
00:38:15,272 --> 00:38:18,984
they would both have survived.

567
00:38:23,656 --> 00:38:24,949
Neither of them…

568
00:38:27,326 --> 00:38:29,412
would have lost their lives.

569
00:38:34,959 --> 00:38:37,002
This is what we believe

570
00:38:38,170 --> 00:38:42,466
to have happened to Yasuo Izawa
on that day.

571
00:38:48,973 --> 00:38:50,099
My husband…

572
00:38:52,351 --> 00:38:55,688
tried to save someone?

573
00:38:58,816 --> 00:38:59,775
Yes.

574
00:39:03,404 --> 00:39:07,241
He tried to save Tamura,
who was about the same age as your son.

575
00:39:09,702 --> 00:39:11,412
He risked his life to do it.

576
00:39:28,137 --> 00:39:29,472
I…

577
00:39:31,390 --> 00:39:33,392
think he was a magnificent person.

578
00:39:46,155 --> 00:39:49,033
Detective! Please listen to me!
This man is--

579
00:39:49,116 --> 00:39:53,204
Overworking employees,
false statements, tampering with evidence…

580
00:39:53,287 --> 00:39:55,956
Plus a whole bunch of further offenses.

581
00:39:57,625 --> 00:40:00,377
Nobuhiko Yamanuki, you are under arrest

582
00:40:00,461 --> 00:40:02,713
for murder and failure to render aid.

583
00:40:05,049 --> 00:40:06,175
It looks like

584
00:40:06,258 --> 00:40:10,012
you're going to spend a lot of time
with us, don't you think?

585
00:40:11,847 --> 00:40:12,932
Let's go.

586
00:40:16,894 --> 00:40:17,853
Move!

587
00:40:18,521 --> 00:40:22,024
Thank you for your cooperation.

588
00:40:23,817 --> 00:40:25,110
You as well.

589
00:40:31,450 --> 00:40:32,535
Thank you,

590
00:40:33,285 --> 00:40:34,578
as always.

591
00:40:40,417 --> 00:40:41,585
From here on,

592
00:40:42,878 --> 00:40:44,755
it's police business, so…

593
00:41:02,356 --> 00:41:06,068
IZAWA

594
00:42:00,831 --> 00:42:05,210
I hope Izawa's feelings reached those two.

595
00:42:08,339 --> 00:42:12,134
Oh. From a forensic science
perspective, the deceased are…

596
00:42:12,217 --> 00:42:14,011
Yes, I get it.

597
00:42:22,061 --> 00:42:23,854
Thank you for today.

598
00:42:23,937 --> 00:42:25,230
Good work.

599
00:42:27,816 --> 00:42:29,151
Wait, Doctor.

600
00:42:29,234 --> 00:42:32,279
That reminds me.
I've actually wanted to ask you…

601
00:42:32,363 --> 00:42:35,699
Why did you want to become
a forensic pathologist?

602
00:42:37,785 --> 00:42:40,663
Well, I wonder why.

603
00:42:40,746 --> 00:42:43,248
For now, it's a mystery.

604
00:42:47,378 --> 00:42:48,837
Good work today.

605
00:43:02,434 --> 00:43:03,394
<i>Masumi.</i>

606
00:43:04,895 --> 00:43:06,188
Stop that.

607
00:43:07,147 --> 00:43:08,857
Don't touch dead things.

608
00:43:13,570 --> 00:43:14,738
Why…

609
00:43:17,950 --> 00:43:19,159
Dad?

610
00:43:19,785 --> 00:43:21,453
KOICHI MIZUSAWA

611
00:43:22,996 --> 00:43:24,540
<i>There is no value</i>

612
00:43:25,332 --> 00:43:26,458
in dead things.

613
00:43:40,431 --> 00:43:43,767
THIRD KILLING BY STRANGULATION THIS YEAR

614
00:43:44,601 --> 00:43:47,646
4TH CASE OF WOMAN FOUND STRANGLED

615
00:43:47,730 --> 00:43:51,024
SHIRAMINE SERIAL FEMICIDE CASE
RESEARCH DATA

616
00:43:53,402 --> 00:43:56,363
AUTOPSY REPORT

617
00:43:56,447 --> 00:43:59,783
SURGEON: MASAHITO KUJO
MARCH 2008

618
00:44:01,160 --> 00:44:04,246
ASSISTANT: MASUMI MIZUSAWA

619
00:44:04,329 --> 00:44:06,582
MASUMI MIZUSAWA

620
00:44:17,551 --> 00:44:20,971
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.

